# Fort Oglethorpe, Georgia

Fort Oglethorpe is a city predominantly situated in [Catoosa County](/Catoosa_County,_Georgia) with some portions extending into [Walker County](/Walker_County,_Georgia) in the [U.S. state](/U.S._state) of [Georgia](/Georgia_(U.S._state)). As of the [2020 census](/2020_United_States_census), the city had a population of 10,423. It is part of the [Chattanooga, Tennessee](/Chattanooga,_Tennessee)–Georgia [Metropolitan Statistical Area](/Chattanooga_metropolitan_area). The city is home to [Lakeview – Fort Oglethorpe High School](/Lakeview_%E2%80%93_Fort_Oglethorpe_High_School), a notable educational institution in the region.

## History

The history of Fort Oglethorpe is deeply intertwined with the military history of the United States. The [United States Army](/United_States_Army) established a cavalry post at the site of Hargrave, Georgia, an unincorporated town situated next to the [Chickamauga National Battlefield](/Chickamauga_and_Chattanooga_National_Military_Park). The existing settlement was named for a [Confederate](/Confederate_States_Army) soldier, William Hamilton Hargrave, who along with his wife Amelia Cecilia Strange-Hargrave owned most of the land in the area. The couple was well known in the 19th century to travelers heading to Ross's Landing on the [Tennessee River](/Tennessee_River) from [LaFayette, Georgia](/LaFayette,_Georgia). William Hargrave and other landowners in the area were forced to sell their property to the Army to be used as a base for the [6th Cavalry](/6th_Cavalry_Regiment).

The Chickamauga Post, established in 1902 by the U.S. Army, was later named [Fort Oglethorpe](/Fort_Oglethorpe_(Fort_Oglethorpe,_Georgia)) after [James Oglethorpe](/James_Oglethorpe), the founder of the [Colony of Georgia](/Province_of_Georgia). During and after [World War I](/World_War_I), the fort served between 1917 and 1920 as a detention camp for [civilian internees](/Internment_of_German_Americans) and [prisoners of war](/Prisoners_of_war). During [World War II](/World_War_II), the area served as a wartime induction and processing center and again housed prisoners of war. Fort Oglethorpe was a major training center for the [Women's Army Corps](/Women%27s_Army_Corps) during World War II. The post land was declared surplus in 1947 and returned to civilian hands, forming the nucleus for a town that was incorporated in 1949.

## Geography

Fort Oglethorpe is located in western Catoosa County and northeastern Walker County at coordinates 34°56′44″N 85°14′44″W (34.945683, -85.245653). It is situated 9 miles (14 km) south of [Chattanooga, Tennessee](/Chattanooga,_Tennessee), by [U.S. Route 27](/U.S._Route_27), which also leads south 18 miles (29 km) to [LaFayette, Georgia](/LaFayette,_Georgia). The [Chickamauga and Chattanooga National Military Park](/Chickamauga_and_Chattanooga_National_Military_Park) takes up the southern two-thirds of the city's area.

According to the [United States Census Bureau](/United_States_Census_Bureau), the city has a total area of 13.9 square miles (36.0 km²), all of which is land.

